{"title":"Synthetic Query Generation using Large Language Models for Virtual Assistants","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Template-based synthetic query generation for VA speech/query priors covers only a narrow set of generic intents and struggles to produce entity-specific, tail-use-case queries needed for emerging entities.","method":"Build an entity-centric prompting pipeline that injects each artist’s Wikipedia lead section (entity description) and name into a fixed intent prompt with examples (e.g., “play, queue, turn on, etc.”) to ask instruction-following LLMs (gpt-3.5-turbo, gpt-3.5-turbo-instruct, gpt-4) to generate K=40 natural VA queries per entity. A knowledge base of 14,161 artists is constructed by linking Wikidata (P2850) and schema.org MusicGroup metadata across Wikipedia and a streaming service; generated queries are normalized to remove VA wakewords. This produces longer, entity-aware queries that reference specific songs/albums and behaviors absent from rigid templates."},{"problem":"It is unclear whether LLM-generated queries both resemble real VA usage and are specific enough to retrieve the intended entity, and whether they add value beyond templates.","method":"Define two quantitative evaluations: (a) domain match via median negative log-likelihood under a Good-Turing-smoothed 4-gram back-off LM trained on two years of anonymized VA queries; (b) specificity via mean reciprocal rank using BM25-L (k1=1.5, b=0.75, δ=0.5) over an index built from each artist’s Wikipedia page and streaming profile. Experiments across all entities show instruction-following LLM queries are more verbose yet similar to VA usage but skew toward tail behavior (higher NLL than entity-name/templates), and are specific enough to retrieve their target entity (avg RR ≈ 0.70), though worse than entity-name/templates; gpt-4 is the weakest among the LLMs and increasing K lowers RR. Very low overlap with templates (mean Jaccard ≈ 0.0038) evidences complementarity, motivating combining both to cover head and tail use-cases."}]}
